By Ngozi Njoku Lagos, – The police in Lagos on Tuesday arraigned two men – Samson Adeyemi, 32, and Joseph Ayomide, 35, charged with conspiracy, unlawful possession of a firearm and membership of a secret cult. The defendants, who reside at Ojota in Lagos State, however, pleaded not guilty to the three-count charge  before an Ogudu Magistrates’ Court. The prosecutor, Insp. Donjour Perezi, told the court that the defendants and others still at large committed the offences on May 3, at 10:30p.m., at Mummy Bar and Suits located on Taiwo Street, Ojota. Perezi said that the defendants possessed an unlicensed locally-made pistol and three cartridges. He added that they belonged to a secrete cult called `Eiye’ Confraternity, in contravention of Sections 42(a), 411 and 330 of the Criminal Law of Lagos State, 2015. The News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) reports that Section 330 provides for a two-year jail term for illegal possession of firearms. The Magistrate, Mrs Bukola Mogaji, granted the defendants bail in the sum of N200,000 with two sureties each in like sum. Mogaji said that one of the sureties must be a blood relation of the defendant. She added that the sureties must be working with reputable organisations and have three years’ tax payment to the Lagos State Government. The magistrate adjourned the case until June 1 for substantive hearing.